        - <span>LIFE | A TRIP TO SAVOUR</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHOTOS: NYTIMES</span>
    </section>

    <p>A par­tic­i­pant mak­ing kimchi (above) dur­ing the Kim­jang Fes­ti­val in Goe­san county in South Korea last month. Fam­i­lies that have grown weary of eat­ing com­mer­cial kimchi in big cities have started mak­ing trips to the coun­try­side, where they learn how to pre­pare the pop­u­lar side dish on their own (left) and store them in clay pots (top). Tra­di­tion­ally, Kore­ans store kimchi in such pots, where the lac­tic fer­men­ta­tion that oc­curs gives the dish its unique taste and tex­ture.</p>

